# DFL Logging and Assertions

## Use Framework Logging

Always use `DeepForestLabs.Logger.Log`, never Unity's `Debug.Log` family.

```csharp
using DeepForestLabs.Logger;

// GOOD
Log.Info("Player connected: {0}", playerId);
Log.Warning("Asset not found: {0}", assetPath);
Log.Error("Failed to load level: {0}", ex.Message);

// BAD -- bypasses framework log filtering, formatting, and frame tagging
Debug.Log("Player connected");
Debug.LogWarning("Asset not found");
Debug.LogError("Failed to load level");
```

Available methods: `Log.Info`, `Log.Warning`, `Log.Error`, `Log.Exception`, `Log.Debug.*`. All support ZString format arguments (`{0}`, `{1}`, etc.) for zero-allocation logging.

## Log.Assert Philosophy

`Log.Assert(condition, message)` validates preconditions at architectural boundaries. It throws `AssertionException` in non-release builds and compiles out in release (`[Conditional("NOT_RELEASE_BUILD")]`).

The DI container guarantees that `[Dependency]` fields are non-null after `Build()`. Trust the container -- do NOT scatter defensive null checks through business logic. Instead, assert at the lowest architectural boundary where a precondition must hold.

```csharp
// GOOD -- trust DI, assert at boundaries
public sealed class WeaponController : Controller<WeaponModel, WeaponView>
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IInputService _input = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly PlayerController _player = default!;

    protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(WeaponView view, CancellationToken token)
    {
        // _input and _player are guaranteed non-null by the container
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            if (_input.FirePressed) { /* fire */ }
        }
    }
}

// BAD -- defensive null checks that DI already guarantees
if (_input != null && _input.FirePressed) { /* fire */ }
if (_player == null) { Debug.LogError("Player is null!"); return; }
```

Use `Log.Assert` when validating data that comes from outside the DI system (user input, deserialized data, editor configuration):

```csharp
Log.Assert(args != null, "args != null, Args not found at '{0}'", MAIN_ARGS_RESOURCES_PATH);
Log.Assert(!string.IsNullOrEmpty(_guid), "!string.IsNullOrEmpty(_guid)");
```

## View SerializeField Validation

Views declare `[SerializeField]` fields with `default!`, establishing a non-null contract. Unity's serialization can silently violate this contract (miswired prefab, missing reference). Validate all required SerializeField references in `OnValidate()` via `Log.Validate` -- never at runtime in `Awake()`, and never null-guard-and-skip in setters.

Views must extend `ValidatedBehaviour` (from the framework), not raw `MonoBehaviour`. `Log.Validate` is `[Conditional("UNITY_EDITOR")]` and fires `[Asset Validation Failure]` messages without crashing.

```csharp
// GOOD -- editor-time validation via ValidatedBehaviour, no runtime cost
#if UNITY_EDITOR
protected override void OnValidate()
{
    base.OnValidate();
    Log.Validate(this, loadedAmmoText != null, "{0} is missing required field {1}", name, nameof(loadedAmmoText));
    Log.Validate(this, reserveAmmoText != null, "{0} is missing required field {1}", name, nameof(reserveAmmoText));
    Log.Validate(this, crosshairRoot != null, "{0} is missing required field {1}", name, nameof(crosshairRoot));
}
#endif

// BAD -- runtime assertion in Awake crashes on instantiation, breaks pool lifecycle
private void Awake()
{
    Log.Assert(loadedAmmoText != null, "loadedAmmoText != null");
}

// BAD -- silently skips when prefab is miswired; broken HUD with zero errors
public void SetAmmo(int loaded, int reserve)
{
    if (loadedAmmoText != null) loadedAmmoText.text = loaded.ToString();
}

// GOOD -- setters trust the contract, no null guards
public void SetAmmo(int loaded, int reserve)
{
    loadedAmmoText.text = loaded.ToString();
    reserveAmmoText.text = reserve.ToString();
}
```

## Dependency Field Convention

Mark injected fields as `private readonly T _field = default!;` (null-forgiving operator). The DI system assigns them during container build. Do not initialize them manually.

```csharp
[Dependency] private readonly IContainer _container = default!;
[Dependency] private readonly CancellationToken _scope = default;
[Dependency] private readonly IMyService _service = default!;
```
